/* The contents of this file are mostly generated by a little helper program.
 *
 * Consider "a square of radius n" (here n = 3):
 * .......
 * .......
 * .......
 * ...@...
 * .......
 * .......
 * .......
 * Actually it's a circle in the walk-metric; hence "radius".
 * In the LOS-algorithm, we need to draw lines, using Bresenham's
 * algorithm, from the center point '@' to each point on the edge
 * of the square (i.e. circle). The algorithm basically produces
 * the points (coordinates) through which the line travels. Now,
 * because our server has a lot of things to do, we, to save time,
 * have a lookup table for all of these coordinates. Actually a
 * bunch of lookup tables, one for each radius, see below.
 *
 * The possible radii are 2--11. That's over 8kb of fairly repetitive
 * lookup data, but it's worth it.
 *
 * (In conclusion, I feel I must mention that, without even noticing the
 * connection until now, I've been listening to "Circle Takes the Square"
 * while typing this...)
 */

